Introduction: The city of Wuhan, not isolated city.

By Suha

It was the first time in New China that a metropolitan area with a population of tens of millions had been shut down as the place where the outbreak began.

But the closure of Wuhan contributed to reducing as many sources of infection as possible. Many experts, including who director-general Tan Desai, believe that the closure of the city will reduce the spread of the disease, they said the move is "very appropriate and very important. ".

From the perspective of National Epidemic Prevention and control, the closure of the city of Wuhan is a strategic decision, but the strategy will eventually be executed with local tactics. As an unprecedented move, it is inevitable that there will be more mistakes in the implementation, but this also shows that some departments and grass-roots awareness of prevention and control is still insufficient, not comprehensive countermeasures.

It has been months since the closure of the city, long-term closure of the city brought about some social problems also began to reveal. Chen Yixin, deputy head of the Central Guidance Group and Secretary General of the Central Political and Legal Affairs Commission, asked on February 22 that the headquarters should keep a clear head and study ahead to come up with effective countermeasures to the many problems facing the city during the prolonged siege.

What happened in the last eight hours

At 2:00 am on January 23, the Wuhan Epidemic Prevention and Control Headquarters issued the first notice: at 10:00 am on the same day, the city bus, subway, ferry, long-distance passenger transport suspended operations, the airport, railway station from the Han passage temporarily closed.

There is an eight hour gap between the time a decision is issued and the time it is executed. That is enough time for some locals to make their own "big decisions" .

According to incomplete statistics, at least 251 trains were dispatched from Wuhan on January 23 between 00 and 10:00, with at least one hundred thousand people scattered across the country by train, from Harbin in the north, Shenzhen in the south, Shanghai in the east and Chengdu in the West.

At about 11:00 am on January 23, the map of Josiah Goddard shows that the main highway exit tollgates in Wuhan are in a severe red congestion -- Foshan -- basically a crowd of people driving away from the city.

Around 12:00 noon, the first finance reporter once saw in Wuhan "East Gate" Qinglong Toll Station, the scene out of the city gate machine access is still unimpeded, vehicles can normal traffic, and into the city vehicles are subject to security checks.

Two hours have passed since the deadline for closing the city.

It wasn't until that afternoon that the road out of the city in Wuhan was completely blocked, hours after the live video, "the east gate of Wuhan is free and clear. ".

At around 2 p.m. , the Hubei Provincial Expressway Administration announced that the entrances to gongjialing, Xiaojunshan, Hannan, Beihu, Hanayama, Baiquan, Qinglong and Xihu stations in the province were closed. The Beijing–Hong Kong–Macau Expressway of the Toll Gates at Wuhan West, Wuhan North, Caidian District and Yong'an will be closed. Other highway crossings out of Wuhan have also been closed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The air passage was not fully closed until noon on January 24. Although the airline canceled most flights involving Wuhan after 10:00 on the 23rd, according to the "soft landing" principle and involving connecting flights, and other reasons, the last flight left Wuhan Tianhe International Airport at 1255 hours on the 24th.

With the gates closed, those who stayed behind and those who could not, began pouring into supermarkets and drugstores to stock up on supplies and protective gear.

In the supermarkets such as Wu merchants, Zhong Bai warehouse and Walmart, people began to scramble for food. "Now we can't care whether the price is expensive or not. It's good to be able to grab food and not go hungry, " said a woman named Liu.

"I stood in line at the supermarket for over an hour and only got two white turnips, " said Ms. Li, who lives in South Lake, Wuchang.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the 23rd, a Sam's Club in Wuhan sold out.

On January 23, our reporter visited the good pharmacist pharmacy and Huiji Pharmacy in the downtown area of Wuhan. Pharmacy staff said the traffic was significantly higher than usual that day, with customers concentrating on buying regular protective products, cold medicine, antiviral drug and infrared thermometers, as well as selling out of protective masks and gloves.

In response, Ye Qing, a member of the Standing Committee of the Hubei Provincial Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference and Deputy Director of the Hubei Provincial Bureau of Statistics, later said that the panic of the public is shared by the people, but the government can do more as if it were to keep information flowing freely, transparent and effective communication, second, the allocation efficiency of medical supplies needs to be improved, the emotional comfort of the public, patient screening and targeted treatment needs to be done more carefully.

Where did five million people go

By blocking Wuhan, we're only controlling the continued output of the original source. And those who have already left Wuhan but may have been partially infected with the virus, where did they go? How do you find and find them? That became the focus.

Wuhan, the thoroughfare of nine provinces, has always been the national water, land and air transport hub, but also an important inflow of migrants to the central region.

On the evening of January 26, at a news conference on the prevention and control of the new crown pneumonia epidemic in Hubei Province, Wuhan Mayor Zhou Xianwang said that as of January 26, more than 5 million people had left Wuhan and 9 million remained in the city because of the Spring Festival and the epidemic.

Where the hell did those five million people go? And suddenly, the whole country was watching.

According to Baidu's migration map, the day before the city was closed, on January 22, the largest number of people left Wuhan, with 71.46 percent of those leaving for cities in Hubei Province. Filial piety (14.56%) , Huanggang (14.08%) and Jingzhou (6.11%) were the most popular.

The evolution of the disease since then has confirmed concerns. As of 2400 hours on February 21, there were 3,429 confirmed cases of new crown pneumonia in Xiaogan, 2,899 in Huanggang and 1,566 in Jingzhou, the three worst affected areas in Hubei Province, outside Wuhan.

In addition to the cities in Hubei Province, people from Wuhan to Xinyang, Chongqing, Changsha, Beijing, Shanghai and Zhengzhou in Henan also had a higher proportion of people leaving the Han Dynasty before the closure of the city.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The big data on migration from Baidu Map, cited by the Institute of first-line cities of Finance and economics, also shows that between January 10 and 22 during the Spring Festival travel period (before the city closure in Wuhan) , six to seven out of 10 people from Wuhan head to other cities in Hubei, followed by Henan, Hunan, Anhui, Chongqing and Jiangxi provinces.

First Business reporter found that in the 20-odd days before Wuhan's closure, up to 60,000 people could fly from Wuhan to Beijing, and more than 50,000 from Wuhan to Shanghai (Hongqiao + Pudong) , Guangzhou and Chengdu.

The five million people who left Wuhan, in addition to the planned return of Spring Festival, but also some in the "closure order" after the people out of the city overnight. Since then, the notification of the epidemic in various provinces in China can be found that people from Wuhan, accounted for the majority of the confirmed cases, and transmitted to a considerable number of local residents.

On January 21st an epidemiologist warned. "The median incubation period of the virus is nine days, " he told China Business News. "current testing equipment can only monitor patients with fever. There is no way to identify carriers of the virus. More provinces are likely to have new cases due to population movements in the future. "

BEDS, supplies!

The siege of Wuhan began to suppress the virus, but at this time the base of the epidemic has begun to expand rapidly, whether medical supplies or diagnostic and treatment capacity, a sudden shortage.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Wuhan Local Hospital Fever Clinic on the 23rd

In order to deal with the possible cross-infection and spread of diseases caused by fever patients seeking medical treatment out of order, a new "7 + 7" model of fever patients seeking medical treatment was initially implemented in Wuhan. That is to say, seven level II public hospitals were selected near seven large hospitals in the urban area as designated hospitals for fever outpatient clinics, and all of the transferred patients and vacated wards were used to receive fever patients. At that time, 3,400 beds were planned to be vacated, we specialize in fever patients.

However, 3,400 beds are simply not enough to accommodate the increased number of suspected and confirmed cases of geometric progression. On January 23, the day of the city closure, the first financial reporter called the 14 designated clinics, except one hospital has a small number of beds, other designated hospitals have been fully occupied.

And Disease Fighting Time, Wuhan Medical System rescue capacity has reached the limit. Video footage circulated online and later confirmed showed front-line medical staff working through tears. Panic is magnified by the concentration of panic patients in the hospital.

WECHAT CIRCLE OF FRIENDS, micro-bo super words, there are people constantly asking for help, asking for help in the home of suspected patients. Because the hospital does not have the sickbed to receive, many diagnoses mild illness patient also has to choose the home isolation.

On Feb. 2, Zhong Nanshan said in an interview that it was dangerous for suspected and confirmed patients to go home and quarantine themselves because there weren't enough rooms.

In addition, a new condition is on the rise -- as if there is no history of exposure, that is, some patients have mild onset without fever.

On January 23, China Business News found that local hospitals in Wuhan were still using a body temperature of 37.3 degrees as a criterion for admission. In confirmed cases, patients who do not have a fever but have been diagnosed with COVID-19 pneumonia have appeared, and 37.3 degrees is no longer the criterion for suspicion. In this way, patients who are pushed home or to other medical institutions may lose the opportunity to be found and treated in the first place, and the virus may therefore continue to spread.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
First Finance issued the same day, called for changes in Wuhan, "37.3 degrees" admission criteria, early detection of infectious source walking. The change is particularly important for detecting carriers, but it also means more beds and medical supplies are still needed in Wuhan.

There are not enough beds in the existing hospitals, so it is necessary to build new ones. More and more people suggest that Wuhan learn from the SARS period of Beijing's "Xiaotangshan Hospital" model, an urgent establishment of a Special Infectious Disease Hospital, centralized treatment of infected patients.

On January 23, the Wuhan municipal government ordered four construction units, including the third construction bureau, to build the Huoshenshan hospital in six days, in accordance with the Beijing Xiaotangshan Model, at the Wuhan Workers'Sanatorium on the Bank of the Zhiyin Lake in Caidian District. The hospital is in the form of board room, one to two storeys high, covering an area of 70 mu, 1000 beds. That night, construction vehicles arrived on the scene.

January 24 morning, the first financial reporter at the scene to see that the excavator after more than 10 hours of uninterrupted operation, has entered the stage of filling stone. Heavy trucks unload the rocks, and bulldozers quickly fill them up. Site construction personnel, there are more than 200 pieces of heavy equipment in continuous operation.

On the afternoon of Jan. 25, Wuhan announced the construction of a new Xiaotangshan Hospital -- Mount Thor Hospital, with 30,000 square meters and 1,300 additional beds, according to the Gross leasable area.

In addition to the problem of beds, the shortage of medical supplies has become increasingly acute.

"We are very short of protective materials, " a government worker told China business news on Jan. 23. "We are also seriously short of hospital beds. "

When Wuhan No. 3 Hospital became a designated hospital, doctors had only a small number of N95 standard medical protective masks, and almost no protective clothing and goggles.

Doctors at Wuhan Jinyintan Hospital said at the time that before entering the ward, the whole body should be disinfected, and each shift lasts four hours. Among them, they can not drink water (to prevent infection) or go to the toilet (to save protective clothing) . After four hours of high intensity, he was sweating profusely in his heavy suit. Working without water or food for 4 or even 10 hours became the practice of frontline medical staff -- including medical crews who came to their aid -- as protective clothing was in short supply.

Within a few days after the city was sealed off, eight hospitals in Wuhan issued announcements one after another, to solicit donations from all sectors of the community goggles, N95 level medical protective masks, disposable surgical masks, medical caps, protective clothing, surgical clothing, anti-shock goggles, protective masks and other materials.

According to the calculation of the relevant departments, as of January 31, Hubei Province can only produce 8 million medical masks, 2 million protective clothing, 1,200 infrared thermometers, can not meet the epidemic prevention needs of the province.

At that time, Wuhan, regardless of medical supplies or diagnostic and therapeutic capabilities, the urgent need for assistance from the whole country.

Since then, a huge medical army has started to reinforce Wuhan. As of February 17, more than 32,000 medical personnel have been sent across the country to support Wuhan in Hubei Province. Numerous materials and medical devices have been sent to Wuhan.

The city of Wuhan is not a fortress.
